## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Fatal at runtime |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Fatal at runtime |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown | Dead code |

### Why It Was Removed

`Thread.Abort()` was inherently unsafe — it could corrupt state by interrupting code mid-execution (inside `finally` blocks, during lock acquisition, etc.). .NET 8 enforces **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The delegate receives a CancellationToken it MUST observe for timely cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, same semantics as the original thread.Join(timeout)
            if (task.Wait(timeout))
                return task.Result;
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Cancellation triggered by our timeout — fall through to TimeoutException
        }

        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }

    // Overload preserving the original signature for fire-and-forget work
    // that cannot be made cancellation-aware. The work will NOT be terminated
    // on timeout — it becomes orphaned (same risk as the original Thread approach,
    // but without the corruption risk of Thread.Abort).
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        Task<T> task = Task.Run(work);

        try
        {
            if (task.Wait(timeout))
                return task.Result;
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is not OperationCanceledException)
        {
            throw;  // Propagate real errors
        }

        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

### Async-first alternative (preferred)

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work,
    TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(timeout);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

### Migration Pitfalls

1. **No forced termination** — Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, there is no way to forcibly kill work in .NET 8. If `work` ignores the `CancellationToken`, it runs to completion as an orphaned task. Every long-running loop, I/O call, or wait must check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or pass the token to async APIs.

2. **`Task.Run` uses the ThreadPool** — The original code created a dedicated `Thread`. If `work` is long-running, use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)` to avoid starving the pool.

3. **`default(T)` with NRT** — In .NET 8 with nullable reference types enabled, `default(T)` for reference types is `null`, which triggers warnings. The `Task<T>` approach eliminates this entirely.

4. **Exception wrapping changed** — `Task.Result` wraps in `AggregateException`; `await` unwraps automatically. Choose the async path to preserve original exception types.

5. **`Task.Wait(timeout)` vs `task.WaitAsync(timeout)`** — `.Wait()` blocks the thread (matches original sync semantics). `.WaitAsync()` is non-blocking but requires `async/await` all the way up the call stack.

**Bottom line:** Prefer the `CancellationToken` overload and make your workloads cooperatively cancellable. The non-cancellable overload is a stepping stone, not a destination.
